crops.description: Juglandaceae. A wild walnut, native to the highlands of northern South America, which resembles closely the black walnut of the United States. The thick-shelled nut contains a kernel of mild pleasant flavor. For previous introduction see 73394.

crops.description: Passifloraceae. An ornamental vine, native to Colombia, with red flowers which are followed by green fruits about 3 inches long. The seeds are smaller and the pulp is not so highly flavored as in some of the other varieties. For previous introduction see 51567.

crops.description: Melanthiaceae. A low bulbous plant, native to the Caucasus, with about five narrow leaves and small clusters of lilac flowers. For previous introduction see 67014.

crops.presented_by: Institute of Sub-tropical Cultures, Sukhum, Transcaucasia (through the Institute of Plant Industry, Leningrad)
crops.institution_involved: Institute of Sub-tropical Cultures, Sukhum; Institute of Plant Industry, Leningrad
crops.description: Iridaceae. A crocus with a very small globose bulb. In the Caucasus region, where it is native, the leaves appear in the spring and remain until the bright-yellow flowers appear the latter part of July and August. The throat of the corolla is yellowish white, the anthers are pale yellow, and the style branches are orange red. For previous introduction see 90616.

crops.description: Liliaceae. A low bulbous plant with two or three linear leaves 3 to 4 inches long and small white flowers in a small dense raceme, on a scape about as long as the leaves. Native to Armenia.

crops.presented_by: Institute of Sub-tropical Cultures, Sukhum, Transcaucasia (through the Institute of Plant Industry, Leningrad)

crops.description: Liliaceae. A squill from the Caucasus with one to three pale-blue suberect flowers more than three-fifths of an inch long. The leaves are oblong-linear or linear lanceolate.

crops.description: Poaceae. Naljara. Collected in the MacDonnell Ranges. A perennial grass with long leafy stolons and short firm leaves. The flowering culms, erect or ascending, are 6 to 18 inches high, and the edible seeds are eaten by the natives.

crops.origin: North of Alice Springs, northern part of central Australia
crops.institution_involved: Collected by Dr. T. G. Strehlow, University of Adelaide, Adelaide
crops.description: Fabaceae. Collected north of Alice Springs, in the northern part of central Australia. Ininta, or bean tree. The red seeds of this tree are used as ornaments by the natives, and the wood is used in the manufacture of shields and putchis (vessels) of all kinds. The beanwood is very light, one of the few soft woods found in central Australia.
